	<h2>'Ayn is for Arab</h2>
	
<p>If we are predisposed to linguistic timidity this is the sound that scares us off. Strictly speaking it is simply the voiced equivalent of <strong>&#1581;</strong><strong>.</strong> But.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I had met Sayed a few months before, in Australia, where he&rsquo;d tutored me in Arabic. Our lessons foundered on the gagging &ldquo;ah&rdquo; sound that has no equivalent in English &ndash; or in any other language. &ldquo;You sound as if you&rsquo;re choking on spaghetti,&rdquo; Sayed would say, correcting me. &ldquo;Just choke. Forget the spaghetti.&rdquo; He usually gave up after fifteen minutes and tutored me in the wiles of Cairo instead. (Tony Horwitz, <em>Baghdad Without a Map</em>, 72-73)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Even a respected linguist makes it sound a little forbidding: &lsquo;Ayn (that&rsquo;s its name) is</p>
<blockquote>
<p>...the voiced pharyngeal fricative, the most characteristic sound of Arabic . . . the throat muscles are highly constricted with the vocal cords vibrating to produce a sound close to a gag.&rdquo; (W.M. Thackston (in <em>Introduction to Koranic and Classical Arabic</em>, xvi)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>A manual teaching the Urdu script, by a linguist who has evidently read Thackston, says that in Urdu the letter is a simple glottal stop, but that in Arabic it was &ldquo;a sound made when the throat muscles are highly constricted and the vocal cords vibrate . . .&rdquo; and adds &ldquo;similar to the sound made when retching&rdquo; (Richard Delaney, <em>Beginner&rsquo;s Urdu Script</em>, 89). William Jones, long ago, in his grammar of Persian (1771) describes the sound in Arabic as &ldquo;harsh,&rdquo; and adds, quoting the 17th-century scholar Franciscus Meninski, that it resembles <em>vox vituli matrem vocantis</em>, which I believe means &ldquo;the sound of a calf calling for its mother.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Jonathan Raban, in an account of his own study of Arabic, resists the &lsquo;Ayn temptation. It&rsquo;s still a difficult sound, but it&rsquo;s not frightening. He even makes it sexy.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I tried to learn Arabic, taking a crash course of a dozen lessons with a lovely Egyptian girl who had a voice that sounded like spring rain and a PhD in Linguistics. We stared solemnly at each other&rsquo;s uvulas &ndash; she inspecting mine to find out why I wasn&rsquo;t making the right noises; I inspecting hers for the sheer pleasure of looking at a piece of apparatus that was capable of producing such enchanting sounds. There is a letter in Arabic, beyond the range of the English palate and the English alphabet, which is usually represented in transcription by a 9. To make the right noise, one has to tie one&rsquo;s vocal cords into a sort of reef knot, then instantly release them, so that for just a split second, in the middle of a word, one sounds like someone being strangled. We struggled for hours over the 9ayn, gurgling together into a tape recorder.</p>
<p>&ldquo;It comes,&rdquo; said Fatma, &ldquo;from deeper in the throat.&rdquo; I never found it. (Tony Horwitz, <em>Baghdad Without a Map</em>, 21)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>There is a 19th-century grammarian of Arabic, Carl Paul Gaspari, who to his credit judged &lsquo;Ayn without panic: &ldquo;Some grammarians have favoured us with descriptions, most amusing absurd, of this <em>indescribable</em> letter&rdquo; (<em>Grammar of the Arabic Language</em>, 9). He includes an extreme example: &ldquo;Vriemoet, a Dutch <em>savant</em>, in his Arabic grammar published at Tranequer, 1733 . . . represents it by <em>hhh!!!</em>, which I suppose means <em>h to the third power</em>.&rdquo; I had my doubts, but <a href="https://books.google.com/books?id=WJpFAAAAcAAJ&amp;printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false">the book exists</a>,&nbsp;and he does in fact transcribe &lsquo;Ayn as hhh. (The exclamation points are, I suppose, Gaspari&rsquo;s comic addition.)</p>
<p class="illo"><img src="../_img/ayn3.png" width="280" align="left" style="margin-left:-80px" /></p>
<p>To my ear the &lsquo;Ayn sound emerges from the throat with much the same value as our English <em>i</em> (as in &ldquo;I&rdquo;). So far no native speaker of Arabic has verified this.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Still, that mispronunciation of the I in Iraq as an &ldquo;eye&rdquo; or &ldquo;I&rdquo; sound is, to my ear, not a bad approximation of the sound &ldquo;Iraq&rdquo; as spoken in Arabic. (I even feel that the standard mispronunciation of &lsquo;Iraq as &ldquo;eye-rack&rdquo; is not far off as we might imagine.) &lsquo;Ayn is for Iraq, but not for Iran. (The first syllable of &ldquo;Iran&rdquo; is just a regular &ldquo;ee&rdquo; sound; the second syllable is that long, characteristically Persian broad A, as in &ldquo;awe.&rdquo; Iran is an Indo-European name, emphatically Indo-European, cognate with &ldquo;Aryan.&rdquo;) Iraq, spelled phonetically <em>&lsquo;ir&acirc;q</em>, starts with the letter &lsquo;Ayn. And yet in Latin letters Iran and Iraq look so similar.</p>
<p>The sounds of letters can bring out the worst in us, whether we give up on a proper pronunciation or whether we try so hard to master it that we become tiresome. Language teachers rarely acknowledge the wisdom of giving up. We can study Arabic without having to pronounce every letter properly, just as we can speak Spanish or Italian without managing a rolled R. Elmer Fudd couldn&rsquo;t pronounce the English R, but it wasn&rsquo;t hard to understand what &ldquo;wascally wabbit&rdquo; meant. There is no harm in saying &ldquo;all right, then, I&rsquo;ll <strong>have</strong> an accent.&rdquo; (We&rsquo;ll have one anyway.)</p>
<p>If all you want to do is read, with the diminished expectations we bring to Latin or classical Greek, you only need to write the problematic letter, or just to recognize it. Anyone can draw an &lsquo;Ayn. At the beginning of a word the shape is something like a lower-case C, a little elongated, with the lower lip extended slightly to the right. In the middle of a word, in its simplest, schoolbook shape &lsquo;Ayn is a more or less equilateral triangle balancing on the baseline, point downward. In proper calligraphy the right shoulder is rounded from the observer&rsquo;s point of view, the left pointed. At the end of a word &lsquo;Ayn ends with a sweeping counterclockwise curve, something like a backwards 3 with a tiny head.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>&#1593;</strong></p>
<p>If you want to form Arabic letters out of a Roman font (as you&rsquo;d see frequently back in the early, font-deprived days of e-mail, when all we had were ASCII characters), &lsquo;Ayn at the beginning of a word (as in &#1593;&#1585;&#1575;&#1602;) traditionally became a lower case c. In medial form it often became, for some reason, a lower-case e. A terminal &lsquo;Ayn required two lines of Roman letters (again, a lower-case c, plus a parenthesis and underscore one line down), and none of it looked that great when you were through.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>c</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong> (_</strong></p>
<p>You&rsquo;ll see the shape of &lsquo;Ayn showing up sometimes in places where you may not anticipate it, standing alone but without a tail ( <strong>&#1569;</strong> ), something like a miniature of the numeral 2, so small it isn&rsquo;t listed with other letters. It&rsquo;s called a Hamza, and it represents a neighboring sound, the glottal stop, a sound English speakers can make just fine (like the T in &ldquo;mountain&rdquo; or in &ldquo;certain&rdquo;). It&rsquo;s a common sight in Persian, Urdu, and all the languages that use the Arabic script. That I know of. In Persian it can mark, on some occasions, the -<em>ye</em> sound of a possessive. It can seem ubiquitous. The word &rdquo;Hamza&rdquo; can also be a name. In Urdu it can be used to mark the space between two vowels. The word &ldquo;Uighur,&rdquo; spelled in Uighur (<strong>&#1574;&#1735;&#1610;&#1594;&#1735;&#1585;</strong> ), starts with a Hamza.</p>
<p>&lsquo;Ayn in Nabataean inscriptions, in medial or final forms, was just a little V shape sitting on the base line. The &lsquo;Ayn we know is more or less the same thing but closed, like an upside down capital Greek Delta (that is, a &Delta;). Written with a reed, it developed some fluidity, but you can still spot the triangle under there.</p>
<p>&lsquo;Ayn goes way back. It&rsquo;s one of those letters which has kept a proper name from Phoenician times (like Alif, Dal, Jim or Sin) rather than just its sound &ndash; a proper name and a totem (like an ox for Alif or a door for Dal). An <em>&lsquo;ayn</em> is an eye (both in Phoenician and in Arabic today). The equivalent letter in Phoenician looked more like an eye, a cartoon eye &ndash; just a circle, sometimes shown with a dot in the middle. At some point (<em>The American Heritage Dictionary</em> says &ldquo;after 900 BC&rdquo;) the Greeks, who had no &lsquo;Ayn sound, used the circle to represent a vowel, our short O. (&ldquo;O&rdquo; had a name in Greek too, sort of, but rather than an actual name it&rsquo;s just a description: omicron, <em>o mikron</em>, the little o, as opposed to <em>o mega</em>, &omega;: Omega, the big one.) So our letter O comes from the same stem as &lsquo;Ayn, and it&rsquo;s not going back.&nbsp;</p>
